                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d482">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.48/1088</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Mr. Eugene H. Dooman, of the Division of Far
                        Eastern Affairs, of a Conversation With the Counselor of the Japanese
                        Embassy</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Yoshizawa</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-30">April 30,
                            1936</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I saw Mr. Yoshizawa yesterday during the reception at the Japanese Embassy and
                    said to him that we are not now in position to give him information beyond that
                    given to the press in regard to the negotiations between the Treasury and the
                    group of Chinese officials and bankers.</p>
                <p>Mr. Yoshizawa said that he hoped that he would be called in whenever the
                    Department felt that it could tell the Japanese Embassy anything in regard to
                    the negotiations.</p>
            </div>
